As an alternative to the hockey stick model, we included the  K -power model (see Fig.  1 ). This model produces smooth dose-response functions and is expected to have better statistical properties. However, also for this model, problems were observed with the coverage probabilities below the expected level. In fact, for none of the outcomes the coverage probabilities of the profile likelihood method was larger than 92%. There are two reasons for the poor performance: a limited sample size and inference on the boundary of the parameter space. For tetanus and diphtheria in the German data, the power parameter  K  was estimated to be far above 1, so the second problem is not relevant, but the decile sample size is low ( \documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
